# 22_dialog_rebuild_pilot — substrate-layer pilot for the dialog-
# rebuild pattern (s199 m1).
#
# Pilot scope: prove that a heap-allocated, self-deleting dialog can
# hold substrate widgets across multiple open/close cycles without
# the registry's duplicate-name throw firing on the second open.
#
# Why this test exists:
#
# Heap-allocated dialogs (ThemeEditDialog, StyleEditorDialog,
# ManageTemplatesDialog, NewDocumentDialog) are constructed on the
# fly with `new ThemeEditDialog(...)` and self-delete via
# signal_close_request → signal_idle delete this. GTK4 destroys
# widgets at idle priority, so the substrate widgets inside the
# dialog don't actually fire their dtor (and the registry
# unregister) until *after* the deferred deletion completes. A
# second open of the dialog reconstructs the substrate widgets —
# and if the previous open's widgets are still in the registry when
# the new ones try to register, ScriptableRegistry::register_object
# throws on the duplicate name and the app crashes.
#
# s191 m7 solved the same problem for the inspector self-rebuild
# case via a recursive walk that called force_unregister
# synchronously on every Scriptable in the subtree, before GTK's
# deferred destruction ran. s199 m1 lifts that walk into
# curvz::utils::force_unregister_subtree and adds it to
# ThemeEditDialog's close handler.
#
# Pilot scope deliberately narrow: only `m_btn_ok` is migrated to
# substrate. Every other widget in ThemeEditDialog stays raw
# Gtk::Button / Gtk::CheckButton / etc. If the pilot works, the
# pattern scales mechanically to the rest of the dialog (next
# session) and to the other heap-allocated dialogs.
#
# The one widget migrated:
#
#   dlg_te_ok    OK button (commits the working buffer and closes)
#
# Modality note: the dialog was modal pre-s199-m1 and is now
# non-modal. The change lets the Scripter window keep focus while
# the dialog is open so this script can run. User-facing behaviour
# otherwise unchanged — OK still commits and closes, Cancel still
# discards and closes, the close-X still discards and closes.
#
# Test protocol — REQUIRES TWO MANUAL DIALOG OPENS:
#
# This script can't open the dialog itself. The Edit-theme button
# on ThemesPanel is the only path to ThemeEditDialog, and
# ThemesPanel isn't substrate-migrated yet (blocked on the
# dynamic-widget naming question — see LEDGER "Open questions").
# Manual opens are bracketed by script runs that drive the
# substrate-side behaviour.
#
#   1. Open Curvz with a fresh / default document and project.
#   2. Open the Scripter window.
#   3. Load this script.
#   4. **Manually**: in the Themes panel (inspector sidebar), click
#      the Edit icon on any theme row. ThemeEditDialog opens. The
#      Scripter stays accessible (non-modal).
#   5. Switch back to the Scripter and run the script. The script:
#        - asserts dlg_te_ok label == "OK"
#        - dlg_te_ok click → on_ok fires, commits, closes window.
#      Close handler runs force_unregister_subtree(m_window),
#      synchronously removing dlg_te_ok from the registry. Idle
#      delete runs after the script line returns.
#   6. **Manually**: click the Edit icon again to reopen the Theme
#      Editor. **This is where the bug would manifest pre-fix** —
#      without force_unregister_subtree, the second open's
#      substrate ctor would throw "duplicate Scriptable name
#      'dlg_te_ok'" and crash Curvz.
#   7. Run the script a second time. Should produce identical PASS
#      results — proves the registry was cleaned and the second
#      open registered fresh.
#
# If both runs PASS and Curvz doesn't crash between steps 5 and 6,
# the pilot is green and the pattern is proven.
#
# DSL note: Button substrate exposes `click` (invoke) and `label`
# (query). The label is a String — quote literals.

#[sub] Dialog OK button — resolves and has the expected label.

assert dlg_te_ok label == "OK"

#[sub] Dialog OK button — click commits and closes.
#[sub] After this line the dialog is closing; force_unregister_subtree
#[sub] runs synchronously inside the close handler, so dlg_te_ok is
#[sub] gone from the registry by the time control returns.

dlg_te_ok click

#[sub] Done. Run this script once per Theme Editor open. If both
#[sub] runs PASS and Curvz didn't crash between manual opens, the
#[sub] force_unregister_subtree pump is doing its job.
